President Obama released a statement on the 45th anniversary of the March from Selma-to-Montgomery, honoring the brave men and women who marched for civil rights. He emphasized the importance of their fight for every American's right to vote, live free, and pursue their dreams. The president praised leaders like John Lewis and President Johnson, who played significant roles in advancing civil rights. While acknowledging the progress made since Selma, President Obama recognized that there is still work to be done. He mentioned his efforts to promote gender equality, protect voting rights, and address the grievances of black farmers. The president also emphasized that the civil rights movement was about enabling Americans of all backgrounds to reach their full potential. He highlighted investments in education, healthcare, and job creation as means to achieve this goal. President Obama concluded by urging everyone to honor the courage of those who marched in Selma and to recommit to the ongoing journey towards equality and justice.